heir families ate, and how people thought about food. Canadians, in turn, rallied around food and nutrition to articulate new visions of citizenship for their postwar future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFood habitszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aFood securityzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aFood supplyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aFoodzCanadaxHistoriography. 0aNutrition policyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWar and societyzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xFood supplyxCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xFood supplyzCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectsxCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311141999240uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482763840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774827638423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774827638/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-141999-2  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles